# Gogo Models, ORM, And Migrations Rules

Use this rule when adding model fields, relationships, query logic, managers,
constraints, indexes, or migrations.

Framework module: `github.com/cybersaksham/gogo`.

## Models And Fields

- Define model metadata with public `models` and `models/fields` APIs.
- Prefer explicit field names, column names, defaults, null/blank behavior,
  validators, choices, indexes, constraints, and relationship metadata.
- Use appropriate field families: scalar, text, numeric, temporal, binary,
  JSON, relation, file, network, PostgreSQL-specific, GIS, generated, and
  choice fields.
- Field coverage includes auto IDs, big auto IDs, small auto IDs, integers,
  big integers, small integers, positive integers, decimals, floats, booleans,
  char/text/email/URL/slug/UUID fields, date/datetime/time/duration fields,
  binary fields, JSON fields, file/image/file-path fields, generic IP fields,
  generated fields, foreign keys, one-to-one relations, many-to-many relations,
  arrays, hstore, integer ranges, decimal ranges, date ranges, datetime ranges,
  geometry, point, line string, polygon, multipoint, multilinestring,
  multipolygon, geometry collection, raster, and grouped choices.
- Keep permissions and content-type expectations close to the app model
  metadata when admin/API/auth behavior depends on them.

## ORM

- Use Gogo ORM querysets, managers, expressions, lookups, aggregates, joins,
  ordering, slicing, prefetch planning, transactions, and locking instead of
  ad hoc SQL.
- Use raw SQL only when the ORM cannot express the query; keep it parameterized
  and close to the app service that owns the behavior.
- Keep query construction in services or managers when it is shared by HTTP,
  admin, API, tasks, or tests.
- Map dialect-specific behavior through public dialect APIs, such as PostgreSQL
  or SQLite dialect packages.

## Migrations

- Add migrations whenever model metadata changes database schema.
- Mark existing tables with `Managed: false` when Gogo should expose metadata
  to ORM, admin, API, serializers, or content types without creating, altering,
  or dropping the table in migrations.
- Keep model metadata valid: no duplicate field names or columns, every
  declared concrete field set needs a primary key, index and constraint names
  must be unique, custom permission codenames must be unique, and registered
  relation targets must exist.
- Keep migration files under the owning app's `migrations/` directory.
- Use public migration operations for creating, altering, renaming, deleting
  models and fields, indexes, constraints, raw SQL, data migrations, and
  safety annotations.
- Treat generated migration `Operations` metadata as the source of truth for
  `migrate` and `sqlmigrate`; migration filenames are not enough to determine
  behavior.
- `makemigrations` compares registered project model metadata with historical
  migration state. Keep custom `DBTable`/`TableName`, field `Column`, field
  `Kind`, nullability, database defaults, indexes, and constraints explicit
  when adopting an existing schema. Field-level `Unique` and `DBIndex` become
  deterministic constraint and index operations rather than catch-all field
  alterations.
- Review generated operations for destructive changes before applying them.
- Keep data migrations idempotent and reversible when possible.
- `go run manage.go migrate` takes a database-backed migration lock before
  applying schema or history changes; a concurrent migration run fails before
  operations execute.
- Use `inspectdb` and `diffschema` before adopting existing tables. Baseline
  with `--fake-initial` only when the live table shape matches the initial
  migration state; missing or mismatched columns, primary keys, nullability,
  types, defaults, or collations must stop the baseline, and unverifiable
  dialects fail closed.
- Use migration commands for normal workflow:

```bash
go run manage.go makemigrations
go run manage.go inspectdb --table <table>
go run manage.go diffschema --app <app>
go run manage.go sqlmigrate <app> <migration>
go run manage.go migrate
go run manage.go showmigrations
go run manage.go squashmigrations <app> <start> <end>
go run manage.go optimizemigration <app> <migration>
```

## Safety

- Do not change existing migration semantics silently.
- Do not edit already-applied migrations unless the project is still private and
  the task explicitly asks for migration history cleanup.
- Prefer additive schema changes for production systems.
